09154nam a22011655i 9781614510680DE-B159720230228123812.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20112011gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)840441167  a97816145106807 a10.1515/97816145106802doi  a(DE-B1597)174819  a(OCoLC)769190339  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aP117 7aLAN0090002bisacsh0481pa400qDE-101  aES 1752rvk0(DE-625)rvk/27814:00aFormational Units in Sign Languages /ced. by Rachel Channon, Harry van der Hulst. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (346 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSign Language Typology [SLT] ,x2192-5186 ;v300tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Phonetics, Phonology, Iconicity and Innateness -- tPart I. Observation -- tMarked Hand Configurations in Asian Sign Languages -- tThe phonetics and phonology of the TİD (Turkish Sign Language) bimanual alphabet -- tChild-directed signing as a linguistic register -- tPart II. Experiment -- tSign language comprehension: Insights from misperceptions of different phonological parameters -- tLexical and Articulatory Influences on Phonological Processing in Taiwan Sign Language -- tWhen does a system become phonological? Potential sources of handshape contrast in sign languages -- tA phonological awareness test for deaf children using Brazilian Sign Language -- tPhonological category resolution in a new Sign Language: A comparative study of handshapes -- tAmerican Sign Language Tone and Intonation: A Phonetic Analysis of Eyebrow Properties -- tPart III. Theory -- tAre dynamic features required in signs? -- tA constraint-based account of distributional differences in handshapes -- tASL Movement Phonemes and Allophones -- tMovement types, Repetition, and Feature Organization in Hong Kong Sign Language -- tLanguage index -- tSubject index0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aSign languages and spoken languages have an equal capacity to communicate our thoughts. Beyond this, however, while there are many similarities, there are also fascinating differences, caused primarily by the reaction of the human mind to different modalities, but also by some important social differences. The articulators are more visible and use larger muscles with consequent greater effort. It is difficult to visually attend to both a sign and an object at the same time. Iconicity is more systematic and more available in signs. The body, especially the face, plays a much larger role in sign. Sign languages are more frequently born anew as small groups of deaf people come together in villages or schools. Sign languages often borrow from the written form of the surrounding spoken language, producing fingerspelling alphabets, character signs, and related signs. This book examines the effects of these and other differences using observation, experimentation and theory. The languages examined include Asian, Middle Eastern, European and American sign languages, and language situations include home signers and small village signers, children, gesturers, adult signers, and non-native signers.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aGrammar, Comparative and generalxPhonology, Comparative. 0aSign languagexPhonology, Comparative. 4aGebärdensprache. 4aPhonetik. 4aPhonologie. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aPhonetics.  aPhonology.  aSign Language.1 aAdam, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnn,